// this is a toy language only. 
// name: llm language 
// the objective of this language is to merge deterministic programming with llms

// one of the main features are the "~=" operator to semantically compare two objects(or values) and return a boolean value.
if ("hi" ~= "greeting") {
    print("hi is a greeting")
} else {
    print("hi is not a greeting")
}
/*
<value> ~= <type> is supported 
<value of type A> ~= <value of type B> is supported 
if a value can be deterministically compared, no need to use llm to compare it. like 20 ~= 20 which is true, also 20 ~= 20.01 can be true, because it is similar and can be done with deterministic programming.
<object> ~= <object> is supported 
<object> ~= <type> is also supported. suppose that we have a struct called "Natural":
type Natural struct {
    value int
}
Natural{value: 20} ~= int // is true 
Natural{value: 20} ~= "number" // is true 
Natural{value: 20} ~= "can be a age" // is true 
// go on 
// other cases will be added in this example some day. 
*/

// btw, we have a builtin function named "prompt" which can be used to prompt the main agent 
response := prompt("what is the meaning of life?") // the default result is a string 
var value Response[int] = prompt("what is 2 + 2?") // but if you want to get a specific type, you need to specify the type in the Response 

// you can create a tool to the llm use:
@tool("this is a tool to get the weather of a city")
func getWeather(city string) string {
    return "sunny"
}

print(prompt("what is the weather of New York?")) // the llm will use the tool to get the weather of New York and return the result. 

// to create new agents:
agent Planner {
    system := "You are a planner agent. You can plan things for the user."
    tools := {getWeather} // subagents needs to explicitly specify the tools they can use.

    // you can define internal attributes for the agent, but they are only accessible if you define internal tools for the agent that access them.
    // or functions. functions/methods are not accessible to the llm, tools need to be defined using the @tool decorator.
    attribute := "value"
    func method() string { // will not be accessible to the llm, but can be used by the tools.
        return this.attribute 
    }

    @tool("this is a tool to get the attribute of the agent")
    func getAttribute() string {
        return method() // can use the internal method to get the attribute.
        // simply return this.attribute would also work
    }
}

// the subagent cant be used by the llm, unless that we implement a tool that invokes subagents.
// to call a subagent, simply call them
Planner.prompt("what is the weather of New York?") // the llm will use the tool to get the weather of New York and return the result.
Planner.prompt("get your internal attribute") // the llm will use the tool to get the internal attribute of the agent and return the result.
print(Planner.method()) // will print "value" because the method is accessible to the main program, but not to the llm.

// btw, a good feature that is not directly related to llms, but can be really useful is to have event system in that language.
event Event {
    id int 
}

emit Event {
    id: 1
}

on Event {
    print("event received with id: " + Event.id)
}

class Person {
    name string 
    func greet() {
        emit Greet {
            who: this.name
        }
    }

    event Greet {
        who string 
    }

    on Greet {
        print("greet event received from: " + Greet.who)
    }
}

emit Person.Greet {
    who: "Alice"
}

on Person.Greet {
    print("greet event received from: " + Person.Greet.who)
} 

// the event system can be used inside and outside a class. but the event is bounded to the scope.

// btw, the agents have builtin events. subagents also have the same events of the main agent. the main agent dont need to access the events as members.
on UserInput {
    print("user input received: " + UserInput.input)
}

on AgentResponse {
    print("agent response received: " + AgentResponse.response)
}

// or

on Planner.UserInput {
    print("user input received: " + Planner.UserInput.input)
}

on Planner.AgentResponse {
    print("agent response received: " + Planner.AgentResponse.response)
}

// this all can be used 
// since this is a toy language, A LOT of details were omitted. the syntax might be a bit different from the possible implementation. the language will also be a transpiled language to golang to take advantage of the concurrency and performance of golang. because of that, a lot of things might be different to respect golang limitations. but the main idea is to have a language that can be used to create agents easily with a DSL like syntax instead of the verbosity of frameworks.

